==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|orient}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|orient}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|oriens||rising; as a noun, the quarter where the sun rises, the east, day}}, present participle of {{m|la|oriri||to rise}}.

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{label|en|transitive}} To familiarize with a situation or circumstance.
#: ''Give him time to '''orient''' himself within the new hierarchy.''
# {{label|en|transitive|figurative}} To set the [[focus]] of so as to [[relate]] or [[appeal]] to a certain group.
#: ''We will '''orient''' our campaign to the youth who are often disinterested.''
# {{label|en|transitive}} To [[point]] at or [[direct]] towards.
#: ''I will '''orient''' all of the signs to face the road.''
# {{label|en|transitive}} To [[determine]] which direction one is facing.
#: ''Let me just '''orient''' myself and we can be on our way.''
# {{label|en|transitive}} To [[place]] or [[build]] so as to [[face]] [[eastward]].
# {{label|en|intransitive}} To change [[direction]] so as to face [[east]].
# {{label|en|by extension}} To change direction to face a certain way.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To place (a map or chart) so that its east side, north side, etc., lie toward the corresponding parts of the horizon; {{lb|en|surveying}} specifically, to rotate (a map attached to a plane table) until the line of direction between any two of its points is parallel to the corresponding direction in nature.

